                            <comment id="28788" author="pjones" created="Wed, 15 Feb 2012 15:14:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Landed for 2.1.1 and 2.2&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21503" author="jay" created="Wed, 19 Oct 2011 13:43:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;it&apos;s too bad for us to have duplicate work.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21502" author="jay" created="Wed, 19 Oct 2011 13:42:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;class_register_type() will register echo_thread/session_key, that&apos;s to say, any keys_init() after registering echo_client will have to allocate a echo_thread_key. However, there is a gap between registering echo_client device and kmem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is this clear?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21480" author="tappro" created="Wed, 19 Oct 2011 08:11:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Jinshan, could you describe how echo_caches may be used before lu_kmem_init()? You mentioned that fact but without any details.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21475" author="tappro" created="Wed, 19 Oct 2011 05:16:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;test fixes are correct but problem is not awk, it is able to work with &amp;gt;1024 bytes. The problem is lprocfs_rd_import in Lustre and it is not fixed. &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-615&quot; title=&quot;sanity test 180a: awk: (FILENAME=/proc/fs/lustre/osc/lustre-OST0000-osc-ffff88032273d800/import FNR=32) fatal error: internal error&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-615&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-615&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; tries to do that.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
